<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title><%= pageTitle %> – Art of the Orient</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <%- include('partials/header', { headerClass, pageTitle }) %>
  <main class="main">
    <h2 class="gallery-title"><%= pageTitle %></h2>
    <section class="section-text section-text-full">
      <p>Ukiyo-e (浮世絵), "pictures of the floating world," are the woodblock prints and paintings that captured the pleasures and transience of Edo-period urban life — kabuki actors, courtesans, famous views, travel, and the changing seasons. From the bold actor prints of Sharaku to the lyrical landscapes of Hokusai and Hiroshige, ukiyo-e combined skilled draftsmanship, innovative printing techniques, and commercial distribution to become one of the best-known Japanese art forms in the world. The genre embraced the fleeting beauty of the everyday and left an enduring mark on both Japanese visual culture and Western modernism.</p>
    </section>
  </main>
  <script src="/js/nav.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
